<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-24 16:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus President to Consult with Greek Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides is flying to Athens next Monday for consultations on
Cyprus issue with Greek Premier Costas Simitis, Government
Spokesman Christos Stylianides said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking after a National Council meeting over recent
developments in the Cyprus issue in view of two new U.N. Security
Council resolutions, Stylianides said Clerides will meet Simitis
next Tuesday to brief him on the views of political party
leaders in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council passed resolution 1217 renewing the
mandate of the U.N. peacekeeping force in Cyprus and resolution
1218 on U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan's good offices mission
in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Stylianides said there will be no new National Council meeting
when President Clerides returns to Cyprus, saying that "the
discussion has been concluded and all parties have expressed their
views".
</P>
<P>
He refused to answer any questions posed by journalists, while
no statements were made by party leaders and representatives
taking part in the National Council, the top advisory body to the
President on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's National Council meeting had been described by
political leaders as "crucial" and "important" and was expected
to deal with the question of deployment of the S-300 missiles.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus signed a deal with Russia in January 1997 to buy
S-300 anti-aircraft missiles in a bid to booster its defense,
a move rejected by Turkey which has threatened to launch a
preemptive strike on the missiles if they are deployed.
</P>
<P>
The resolutions were described as positive by Nicosia and
satisfactory by Athens, while they were also welcomed by the
U.S., Britain and the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash on the
other hand, rejected them and repeated their demands for a
confederation of two states on the island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when
Turkish landed its troops and took over the northern third of
the island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union
with Athens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
