<HEADLINE> Lusaka City Council Urged to Improve Road </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba Thursday called upon the Lusaka City Council LCC) to put
the roads under a systematic road maintenance program so as to
save them from deteriorating to poorer condition.
</P>
<P>
The lack of proper drainage systems on roads in the capital
and other parts of the country have made many roads damaged by
rains, the president said here at the hand-over ceremony of a
Lusaka road rehabilitation project.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the accelerated urban roads rehabilitation
of Lusaka priority roads covers 54.2 kilometers, Zambia News
Agency ZANA reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba further urged the LCC to provide street lighting, road
signs and good water drainage systems on the newly-constructed
roads.
</P>
<P>
ZANA quoted him as saying that the government recognized the
importance of roads as major backbone infrastructure for social
and economic development of the country.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba also said good road networks play an important role in
the economic activities because they attract investment
opportunities in the country.
</P>
<P>
He noted that over the past years, limited resources were
allocated to the road sector and to the upkeep of the road
networks, resulting in a backlog of road rehabilitation and
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
This has over a long period escalated road repair costs,
vehicle operating costs as well as road safety problems. Due to
bad roads, a number of road accidents have taken place resulting
in many deaths, he said.
</P>
<P>
The president assured Zambians that what had been done in
Lusaka would be replicated to the cooperating partners to support
the program.
</P>
<P>
"We are fully convinced that this program will provide a
conducive environment in our major urban areas to promote social
and economic activities, thereby reducing the high levels of
poverty in our communities," Chiluba said.
</P>
<P>
According to the Local Government and Housing Ministry, the
first phase of the roads rehabilitation which covered 47 roads
was over and the second phase has been started which would cover
49.4 kilometers involving 48 roads and sites for rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Lusaka mayor and city council officials showed
President Chiluba around the new roads. 
</P>
</TEXT>
