<HEADLINE> U.S. Personal Income Increases 0.5 in November </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. personal income
picked up 0.5 percent in November, the largest gain since
February, the Commerce Department said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The last month increase in personal income followed respectable
gains of 0.4 percent in October and 0.3 percent in September.
</P>
<P>
With the holiday shopping season coming, personal spending
crept up just 0.1 percent and personal savings rate was only 0.1
percent in November.
</P>
<P>
However, the savings figures were not as bleak as they
appeared, the Department said. They indicated people were spending
some of the wealth they had accumulated in the stock market and
cashing in a portion of their home equity. At present, consumer
spending is powering the U.S. economy at a brisk growth rate.
</P>
<P>
The most important component of income--wages and salaries rose
0.6 percent last month, while income in manufacturing were flat,
reflecting U.S. trade problems. But it rose 0.9 percent in
services, which is less affected by international competition.
</P>
</TEXT>
