<HEADLINE> Canada's GDP Up 0.2 Percent in October </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Canada's gross domestic product
(GDP) edged up 0.2 percent in October, Statistics Canada reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It was the third straight monthly increase in the country's GDP
following a four-month stretch of weakness.
</P>
<P>
The October growth was sustained in large part by post-strike
recoveries in auto manufacturing, air transportation and
education, the statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
"Excluding these three industries, activity in the rest of the
economy fell 0.3 percent" in October, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
On an annual basis, Canada's GDP was up 2.0 percent over the
same month of 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Growth in 1998, while generally maintaining an upward trend,
has slackened considerably from 1997's steeper pace," the agency
noted.
</P>
<P>
"Weakness so far this year has been concentrated in the
goods-producing sector of the economy," it said.
</P>
<P>
In October, the country's manufacturing production posted a 0.7
percent gain for a third consecutive month. But when auto sector is
excluded, the remaining manufacturing output fell 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The end to strike by Air Canada pilots led a 2.8 percent
increase in the transportation and storage services in October.
Activity in the air transport industry soared by 21.5 percent,
surpassing the pre-strike level by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, education services rose 1.6 percent after
striking teachers returned to work in the country's most populous
province of Ontario. 
</P>
</TEXT>
