<HEADLINE> India to Pursues Outward-looking Foreign Policy: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Indian would pursue an
outward-looking foreign policy in the new year with special focus
on economic diplomacy and a pragmatic approach to resolve
problems, Minister of External Affairs Jaswant Singh said here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In his first press conference since he took over as external
affairs minister earlier this month, Singh said India was
committed to improving relations with China so that all
outstanding issues were resolved in accordance with the five
principles of peaceful co-existence.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he had any plan to visit Beijing next year, Singh said
his schedule for the new year would be finalized by the
departments concerned.
</P>
<P>
He said that his ministry would make efforts to enhance the
economic cooperation with its neighbors and member countries of
the South Asia Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC).
</P>
<P>
India would take measures to ensure economic and energy
security in 1999, he said, claiming that a strong and stable India
would contribute to regional peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that his country would also engage in
dialogues at different levels with the United States, China,
Russia, Japan and European countries.
</P>
<P>
He ruled out any rollback of India's nuclear program, asserting
that New Delhi would maintain credibility of its nuclear
deterrence and would not compromise on the national security
interests.  
</P>
</TEXT>
