<HEADLINE> Workshop Suggests Special Team for Soil Fertility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 24 (Xinhua) -- A regional workshop
concluded Thursday in Lalitpur which neighbors Kathmandu suggested
the formation of a special team comprising all the member nations
of the South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC)
for improving the region's soil fertility.
</P>
<P>
The special team shall make necessary arrangements and carry
out works toward the end, suggested experts attending the two-day
workshop on "soil fertility management under watershed approach,"
the Nepali RSS news agency said.
</P>
<P>
About 15 soil experts from Bangladesh, Bhutan, Nepal and Sri
Lanka participated in the workshop jointly organized by the Nepal
Agriculture Research Council and the SAARC Division of Nepali
Foreign Ministry. India, the Maldives and Pakistan, the three
other SAARC member states, were absent.
</P>
<P>
The workshop focused on such issues facing the region as soil
erosion, decline in soil fertility, insufficient and unbalanced
use of chemical fertilizers, destruction of forest and pasture
land, continuous cultivation of single crops, obstructions in
irrigation and lack of laws and regulations regarding the use of
soil, RSS said.
</P>
<P>
To address the problems, the workshop stressed, among others,
increasing use of compost fertilizers, monitoring and publicizing
of agro-forests, identification and cultivation of cash crops and
increasing the standards of domestic fertilizers.
</P>
<P>
Other suggestions included development of soil conservation
technologies and irrigation, afforestration, improvement in
scientific methods of farming, coordination with neighboring
countries and soil testing and integrated crop nutrition
management, RSS said.
</P>
<P>
The experts presented reports on fertility management of soil
following the watershed concept in their respective countries, the
news agency added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
