<HEADLINE> France Suspends Surveillance Flights over Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 24 (Xinhua) -- France has suspended the
surveillance flights by its spy plane over Iraq since the
U.S.-British air strikes last week, reported the daily Le Monde on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
France participated in the U.S.-led surveillance flights over
southern Iraq with a Mirage IVP strategic reconnaissance aircraft
to help the UNSCOM look for undeclared arms production and arms
stocks sites.
</P>
<P>
The spy plane and five Mirage-2000 combat aircraft of France
are based in the Al Kharg military base in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the five Mirage-2000 aircraft, which participated in
the U.S.-led ``Southern Watch'' operation imposing a no-fly zone
in southern Iraq, has stay grounded since the beginning of
``Desert Fox'' operation.
</P>
<P>
France suspects that the U.S. would use the means of ``Southern
Watch'' to reinforce the ``chain of command'' of U.S. general
Anthony Zinni who was in charge of the ``Desert Fox'' operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
