<HEADLINE> Russian Duma Approves 1999 Budget in First Reading </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Russian State Duma lower
house of parliament on Thursday approved the government's 1999
budget in the first reading.
</P>
<P>
The majority of deputies who voted in favor are members of the
Communist Party, the Liberal Democratic Party of Russia and the
Our Home is Russia movement.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who earlier threatened to
resign if the budget draft was shot down, hailed the approval as a
show of political support for his government.
</P>
<P>
The budget provides for a spending of 575 billion rubles and
revenues of 473.6 billion rubles with a deficit of 101.3 billion
rubles, or 2.54 percent of gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
"We are very satisfied that the Duma passed the budget plan in
the first reading," he said.
</P>
<P>
The approval came after Primakov agreed to the Federation
Council's demand that the federal budget and regional budgets
share tax revenues equally.
</P>
<P>
In total, 303 Duma deputies voted for the draft, far exceeding
the required 226 votes. Sixty-five deputies voted against with
nine abstentions.
</P>
<P>
In the Communist Party faction, 115 deputies backed the budget
plan, three voted against and ten did not vote at all. Duma
Chairman Gennady Seleznyov and Communist Party Chairman Gennady
Zyuganov voted in favor.
</P>
<P>
Gennady Seleznyov, speaker the of State Duma, said the draft
will be submitted for its second reading in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
"Intensive preparatory work for the second reading will begin
now," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
