<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Conducts Non-Nuclear Tests </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 24 (Xinhua) - The Russian Atomic Energy
Ministry announced Thursday the completion of five non-nuclear
tests at the Novaya Zemlya test site in the Arctic.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Atomic Energy Minister Lev Ryabev said all the
experiments were conducted in strict compliance with the nuclear
test ban treaty, although military-grade plutonium and
highly-enriched uranium were used in underground tests, Interfax
reported.
</P>
<P>
The tests, carried out between September 14 and December 13,
are designed to check the safety level of the nuclear potential
and the efficiency of new efforts to increase the reliability and
security of nuclear weapons and also to study the possibility of
extending the warrantied age of nuclear arms, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
There was no nuclear emission, Ryabev said, noting that the
tests were conducted in special sealed containers and that no
damage was done to the environment.
</P>
<P>
He said the Atomic Energy and Defense Ministries will conduct
more such experiments in the future.
</P>
<P>
The experiments also are intended to study how the components
of the weapons may change over long periods of storage, Ryabev
said, adding that the United States has conducted similar
research. 
</P>
</TEXT>
