<HEADLINE> U.S. Warns Americans from Traveling to Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
on Thursday warned Americans not to travel to the west African
country of Sierra Leone where fighting between rebel forces and
Nigerian-led intervention troops intensified this week.
</P>
<P>
The State Department also ordered all U.S. government personnel
to leave the country after suspending operations at its embassy.
</P>
<P>
The State Department said in a statement that travel to Sierra
Leone was extremely hazardous because of possible attacks by
deposed military and rebel forces.
</P>
<P>
"U.S. citizens in Sierra Leone should review their personal
security situation and are urged to depart the country," the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah was restored to power in March by
West African forces after the ruling military junta that deposed
him was ousted. But that could not end the fighting between them.
</P>
<P>
The ousted junta forces rallying rebels, who had been fighting
since 1991, have remained active outside the capital of Freetown
since Kabbah's return. 
</P>
</TEXT>
