<HEADLINE> Eritrea Urged to Accept Peace Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Foreign
Ministry Thursday called on the international community to put
pressure on Eritrea to accept the peace proposals endorsed by the
recent summit of Central Organ of the Organization of African
Unity (OAU).
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here by the Ethiopian Foreign Ministry
said: "Proposals have now been endorsed by the Central Organ
of the OAU at a summit level on December 18, 1998 in Ouagadougou
which also called for its speedy implementation."
</P>
<P>
The press release said the core elements of the proposals are
to request that Eritrea pull out its troops from all occupied
Ethiopian territory and demand for the restoration of the
Ethiopian administration with all its law enforcement organs.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the "OAU effort requires the effective support
of the international community which no doubt continues to bear
great responsibility for giving diplomacy a chance or for making
diplomacy lose all momentum with all its consequences."
</P>
<P>
"It is time for those with real and genuine commitment for
peace in our sub-region to stand up and be counted," the press
release urged.
</P>
<P>
The Ouagadougou summit endorsed the proposals for a framework
agreement, submitted by the OAU High Level Delegation, for a
peaceful settlement of the dispute between Eritrean and Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The 11-point proposals include immediate cessation of
hostilities, creation of conditions conducive to a comprehensive
and lasting settlement of the conflict, withdrawal of Eritrean
troops from Badme Town and its environs to positions they held
before May 6, 1998, redeployment of a group of military observers
and delimitation and demarcation of the border between the two
countries within a time frame of six months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
