<HEADLINE> Egypt Condemns Israeli Killing of Lebanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa Thursday condemned the killing of Lebanese civilians by
Israeli troops in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on a recent Israeli atrocity, Moussa underlined that
the life of a Lebanese or Palestinian civilian is not in any way
less important than that of an Israeli.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Israel's apology for what it termed as
"accidental" killing of Lebanese civilians, Moussa slammed the
Israeli logic as setting a precedent that the "aggressor would
kill civilians before saying sorry."
</P>
<P>
He poured scorn on Israel's apology, saying that the Jewish
state will "always have to remember" that it has destroyed an
entire Lebanese family.
</P>
<P>
Israeli troops launched a sustained air raid last Tuesday in
south Lebanon, claiming the lives of eight Lebanese civilians,
including a woman and her six children.
</P>
<P>
International laws and conventions prohibit targeting
civilians in times of war, he said, demanding Israel's respect for
the international laws.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-styled security zone in south Lebanon in
1985 with a claimed aim of protecting its north from Lebanese
guerrilla cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, has been
spearheading a guerrilla war against the Israeli occupation troops.
</P>
<P>
Israel has claimed the killing of the family a "mistake," which
was refuted by the U.N. peacekeeping force in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the U.N. force had said that the house in which
the family was living is hundreds of kilometers away from the
Israeli border and no military actions have been taken in its
vicinity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
