<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North Pole Once as Hot as Modern Florida </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. scientists say the
North Pole, one of the coldest places in the world, was as warm as
today's Florida some 90 million years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest issue of Science, fossil findings from
the far north confirm that the Arctic once enjoyed roughly the
same climate as modern Florida.
</P>
<P>
Geophysicist John Tarduna and his colleagues wrote in Science
that the warming was part of a global spike in temperatures that
was apparently caused by a dinosaur-era version of the "greenhouse
effect."
</P>
<P>
Paleontologists have long known that the Arctic was much warmer
during the Cretaceous period, which lasted from 144 million to 65
million years ago. The discovery of the remains of a
crocodile-like carnivore with a long snout could not survive if
temperatures dipped below freezing.
</P>
<P>
U.S. scientists say the warming was attributed to the extreme
volcanic activity that spewed prodigious amounts of heat-trapping
carbon dioxide into the atmosphere.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
