<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Association for the
Blind of Ethiopia Thursday urged higher educational institutions
in the country to respect rights of students with visual
impairment.
</P>
<P>
Opening a one-day meeting here on problems encountered by the
blind, Kassahun Tibeltal, chairman of the Association, said
that visually impaired students learning at higher educational
institutions in the country are enduring several hardships.
</P>
<P>
Some higher educational institutions refuse to
enroll blind students, Kassahun was quoted by the Ethiopia News
Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said those who have been enrolled would be forced to drop
out due to lack of necessary support.
</P>
<P>
According to Kassahun, the decision made by the Oromiya
regional educational bureau this year to prohibit the blind and
disabled persons from studying at the Jimma Teachers Training
College contravenes the country's policy and constitution.
</P>
<P>
Six visually impaired students who had been prevented from
joining the college because of the decision of the bureau are
sitting idle, he said.
</P>
<P>
There are 150 visually impaired students at the Addis Ababa
University and Kotebe Teachers Training College, he said, adding
that "they face a lot of problems."
</P>
<P>
The meeting is organized to find solutions to the problems
blind students are faced with. 
</P>
