<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Amends Customs Tariffs Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus amended its Customs
Tariffs Law to bring Cyprus in line with European Union (EU)
standards and world trade practices, the Cyprus Weekly newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under the amendment approved by the House of Representatives,
duty-free status will be extended to some raw materials until June
2000. And the extension will also cover such commodities as milk
powder, chocolate and fruit juices.
</P>
<P>
Raw materials used in manufacturing margarine have also been
put into this category.
</P>
<P>
The coefficient of the Joint Foreign Customs Duty regulations,
which the EU will enforce for the second half of 1999, is also
adopted, with the exception of processed coffee for retail trade,
cigars and cigarettes, for which duties reduction will come into
effect on July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Consumer tax has been lifted on such items as decorative live
fish, furs, fur clothing, bathtubs and lighters.
</P>
<P>
Tax exemption on gifts sent by mail is increased from 50 cents
(about one U.S. dollar) to 2 Cyprus pounds (about 4 dollars) per
parcel.
</P>
<P>
The House ratified the amendments unanimously on the
recommendation of the Finance Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
