<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Announces Evacuation of One-Third Staff Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations is
evacuating about a third of its 116 staff from Sierra Leone but
leaving the rest of its workers in the West African nation where
rebel forces have strengthened military offensives, a U.N.
spokesman announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Manoel de Almeida e Silva, told a press
conference that some 40 employees, mainly civilians, were being
sent to neighboring Guinea, while others in outlying regions were
moved to Sierra Leone's capital of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has a 60-member peacekeeping operation of
troops, military observers, police and medical staff, known as the
U.N. Observation Mission in Sierra Leone. It also has civilian
humanitarian staff and administrators.
</P>
<P>
Rebel infiltrators attacked villages around Freetown earlier
this week in hit-and-run raids, which were the closest to the city
since a Nigerian-led West African peacekeeping force, called the
ECOMOG, restored President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah to power in March.
</P>
<P>
Renegade soldiers toppled Kabbah in May 1997, and rebels, who
had been fighting since 1991, rallied to their coup.
</P>
<P>
The rebels and the coup loyalists have remained active outside
the capital since Kabbah's return to power in a notorious campaign
against thousands of civilians.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Wednesday issued a presidential
statement, calling for an end to the foreign support and
participation of the rebel's attacks and to atrocities on
civilians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
