<HEADLINE> Nepal Forms 11-Member Cabinet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala, who was sworn in Thursday, formed Friday an
11-member cabinet which is responsible for conducting free, fair
and impartial elections by March/April 1999.
</P>
<P>
King Birendra, on the recommendation of Koirala, appointed
Friday 10 ministers including one from the Upper House of
Parliament nominated by himself, Radio Nepal said.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Koirala holds concurrently the portfolios of
foreign and defense affairs, royal palace affairs, agriculture,
labor, forest and soil conservation, land reform and management,
works and transport, supplies and housing and physical planning.
</P>
<P>
His Nepali Congress (NC) also holds the posts of home affairs,
education, information and communications and youth, sports and
culture while its major partner Communist Party of Nepal (United
Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) gets the key ministries of finance,
local development, water resources and tourism and civil aviation.
</P>
<P>
The Nepal Sadbhavana Party, the minor partner in the
tri-partite government, was offered the post of industry minister
held by its President Gajendra Narayan Singh.
</P>
<P>
Ramesh Nath Pandey, minister for environment and population,
became the first member of Upper House to be nominated by King
Birendra into the government.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement reached Sunday between the NC and the
CPN-UML, the cabinet shall be small for the elections. But it is
expected to be expanded later for the induction of other parties
in parliament willing to join the coalition government, the sixth
since the mid-term polls in November 1994.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of political turmoil erupted when the
Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism, CPN-ML) pulled out of
the coalition government with the NC on December 10.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-ML alleged that the NC had failed to implement the
agreements reached with it and other left parties in August.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition CPN-UML, from which the CPN-ML broke away
in March this year, threw its weight behind Koirala after his
party agreed to form an all-party government for conducting new
elections.
</P>
<P>
Koirala resigned Monday to make way for the formation of such a
government. He was reappointed prime minister Wednesday by King
Birendra.
</P>
<P>
The CPN-ML now becomes the main opposition party in parliament.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
