<HEADLINE> Malaysia Hopes UN to Form Special Body to Resolve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Friday expressed
hope that the United Nations (UN) will agree with any efforts to
form a new UN Special Commission to resolve the problem in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi said Friday he
was told that France would take the initiative to set up the new
commission to replace the existing one which had failed to gain
the confidence of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia is prepared to discuss the matter in New York if it
was raised, he said in Kepala Batas, northern state of Pulau
Pinang, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said Malaysia would urge the UN to organize peaceful
discussion on the situation in Iraq which was recently under
U.S.-British air and missile attacks.
</P>
<P>
"Military aggression is not the way to resolve problems because
it could lead to hatred among the people against the countries
which attack them," Abdullah was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia's stance was to avoid any form of military
action to force another country to accept a directive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
