<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi, Indian Officials to Start Joint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Officials of Bangladesh and
India will start joint monitoring of the Ganges waters at Farakka
Barrage in India and Hardinge Bridge point in Bangladesh's
Ishwardi from January 1, the beginning of five-month lean period,
Associated Press of Bangladesh (APB) reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The joint-monitoring of the flow of waters of the Ganges,
called Padma inside Bangladesh territory, by the two countries
during the lean period has been envisaged in the 30-year water
sharing treaty signed between them on December 12, 1996.
</P>
<P>
A two-member expert team from Bangladesh left here for India
last Saturday for observing the flow of the Ganges at the Farakka
Barrage point.
</P>
<P>
Under the water-sharing formula, Bangladesh is to get 67,516
cubic feet per second of water during the first 10-day cycle from
January 1.
</P>
<P>
The flow of the Padma is presently over 100,000 cubic feet per
second, according to an engineer of the Water Development Board.
</P>
</TEXT>
