<HEADLINE> Rwanda Denies Having to Do With Lusaka Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government denied
that the Lusaka summit was postponed because it was not happy
with a proposed cease-fire between Congolese President Laurent
Kabila and the rebels, Rwanda News Agency (RNA) said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We have been preparing ourselves to attend the Lusaka
meeting, we were ready to go there but were told on Thursday that
it was postponed," RNA quoted Rwandan Minister of Foreign Affairs
and Cooperation Anastase Gasana as saying.
</P>
<P>
Gasana said this in response to media reports that the summit
was put off because Rwanda was not happy about some clauses of
the content of the cease-fire which was expected to be signed in
Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
The reports had quoted diplomatic sources at the Organization
of African Unity (OAU), alleging that the Lusaka summit was
adjourned because the facilitator could not secure sufficient
agreements.
</P>
<P>
However, there has been not any reaction from the Zambian
authorities who were supposed to host the meeting.
</P>
<P>
It has been alleged that Rwanda and Uganda who are backing the
rebels are split on whether they should sign the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the OAU headquarters have been quoted as saying
that while Uganda would like to see the end of the war, Rwanda
reportedly was unhappy with the cease-fire deal.
</P>
<P>
"These allegations are just lies," Gasana told RNA, "because
even in Ouagadougou I was ready to sign the deal on behalf of the
Rwandan government had it been concluded."
</P>
<P>
"Our position on the Congolese conflict was made known to the
OAU secretary general, and we could not have changed our mind
ever since," Gasana underscored.
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources in Kigali said the Lusaka summit was not
well prepared, and that the dates were chosen without considering
that the meeting was following between two important holidays,
Christmas and the New Year.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan foreign minister disclosed that a number of
countries, notably Tanzania and Burkina Faso had expressed
dissatisfaction with the choice of the dates, which would have
implied that delegations would have started to travel to Zambia
on Christmas.
</P>
<P>
"The summit was simply postponed because the facilitator
feared to get a poor attendance, for some delegations had
indicated that they might not be able to come," said Gasana.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that Rwanda will always support any peace deal
reached by President Kabila and the rebels. This deal would be
followed by a more comprehensive one which would address the
concern of the neighbors of Congo involved in the war, notably
Rwanda and Uganda.
</P>
<P>
"The Congolese government may have supporters, the rebels may
have supporters too, but once they strike a deal to end the war,
everybody should follow suit," Rwandan Minister in President's
Office Patrick Mazimhaka insisted.
</P>
<P>
"It is mainly their own war, not ours," he pointed out.
</P>
</TEXT>
