<HEADLINE> Scientists Study Sea-Farming Capacity in Bays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- An international project, to
be done by more than 40 scientists from France, Britain, Portugal
and China, will start next year to study the sea-farming capacity
in Chinese bays.
</P>
<P>
The project, to be funded by the European Union, will also
study the impact of aquiculture to the marine environment and help
China sustainably develop its aquiculture industry.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the death rate of Chinese sea farms is growing
and their production and economic efficiency is dropping, said an
expert from the Institute of Oceanology of the State Oceanic
Administration.
</P>
<P>
The study will be conducted in Sanggou Bay and Jiaozhou Bay in
east China's Shandong Province, which are totally different in
environment and varieties of products.
</P>
<P>
Through analysis to the ecological system in the sea farms,
scientists want to find the balance between sea-farming capacity
and environment, which means to keep the largest production scale
and pose no harm to the environment.
</P>
<P>
Scientists believe that the scientific achievements can also be
applied in other coastal countries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
