<HEADLINE> Pak Urges U.S. to Lift Military Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz Friday urged the United States to lift military
sanctions against Pakistan in the face of the recently-signed
India-Russia defense pact.
</P>
<P>
"We will take up this issue with the United States in the
forthcoming talks and press for lifting the military sanctions as
there is greater urgency for that in the face of India-Russia
agreement," he was quoted as saying by the Associated Press of
Pakistan (APP) in an interview.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Islamabad would also take up the issue with New Delhi
during their scheduled talks on issues of peace and security and
the Kashmir dispute in February next year.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that there is already disparity in the
conventional arms between Pakistan and India and with New Delhi
getting more arms from Russia under the pact, it will further
affect the balance of power in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Minister noted that during his recent visit to the
United States, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif had expressed concern
that such a pact was in the offing and now that it has actually
taken place. Washington should remove military sanctions against
Pakistan, said Aziz .
</P>
<P>
He questioned the purpose of the India-Russia pact which
provides for massive arm purchases by India from Russia worth 16
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
"This unusual addition in defense purchases by India and the
pact are not in spirit of reconciliation in the region," he said.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, Aziz said, is for restraint but with this agreement
India has introduced a new element of threat in the region.
</P>
</TEXT>
