<HEADLINE> Iraq Declines UAE Aid Shipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi government has
returned a shipment of aid from the United Arab Emirates and
called on Arab countries to play an effective role in removing
U.N. sanctions, the Gulf News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi authorities have returned a ship carrying donations,
including food, medicine, blankets and clothes, according to
Mohammed Abdullah Al Sheibah of the Needy Muslims Committee which
sent the ship.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has said that aid ships from Arab countries are not of
any help to the 20 million people in the country who have been
suffering because of the sanctions since 1990.
</P>
<P>
"According to the Iraqi authorities, the only way to help the
people would be for the Arab countries to take a unified stand and
intensify efforts to press the international community to remove
sanctions, and not just send aid and donations," said Al Sheibah.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government took the decision not to accept aid about
six months ago, but Al Sheibah said the committee continued to
send aid, by road, via Jordan.
</P>
<P>
This time, while sending back the ship carrying aid, the Iraqi
government said an added reason for doing so was that the Umm Qasr
port had been badly damaged in the recent joint air strikes
carried out by U.S. and British forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
