<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Debate Citizens Chance To Appeal Official Decrees (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese citizens should be
entitled to appeal against government violations of their
interests and also against "illegal" government decrees and
regulations, Chinese lawmaker Yang Zhenhuai said today.
</P>
<P>
Yang, a member of the National People's Congress Standing
Committee, made the proposal when reviewing the draft law on
administrative appeals at the ongoing legislative session.
</P>
<P>
The existing draft originally submitted by the State Council
provided that the law shall cover "specific administrative
activities" that citizens claim infringe upon their rights and
interests.
</P>
<P>
Yang said that the word "specific" should be deleted, and
most of the lawmakers shared his opinion.
</P>
<P>
If such a clause is incorporated, it means that the public
will be able to appeal against certain government rules and
regulations that may be contrary to the Constitution and the Law.
</P>
<P>
Yang pointed out to his colleagues that the most common
complaints of the public, such as what are the essentially illegal
collections of exorbitant fees by local governments, directly
derive from "illegal" and unreasonable government orders and
regulations.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes these law-breaking activities of certain government
employees are following written government orders," he added.
</P>
<P>
Observers at the legislative session commented that the
existing 8-year old law on administrative procedures does not
encourage or support lawsuits against such "unofficial" government
activities. If a clause ensuring this could become a part of that
law it would, they say, be a major breakthrough in China's
legislative system.
</P>
<P>
However, the NPC LAW Committee explained that the current draft
does not yet cover this "unofficial" subject, because it is a very
important and complicated issue and needs to be further discussed
by lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Yet another lawmaker, Ruan Chongwu, said that the public should
be allowed such a channel to air their complaints and have them
redressed, otherwise social disturbance will ensue.
</P>
<P>
"Some of today's government regulations are really factors
towards instability," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
