<DOCNO> XIE19981225.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Debate on Whether Citizens Can Appeal Government Decrees (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Peng Peiyun, vice-chairperson of the NPC Standing Committee,
rejected the possibility that such "illegal" government rules and
activities could be investigated and redress made if necessary,
because the task would be tremendous.
</P>
<P>
She agreed, however, that giving the public the right to appeal
against government orders is an effective way to strengthen the
public's monitoring of government and over the implementation of
the law.
</P>
<P>
Many lawmakers also suggested that the draft law should make
the State Council, or China's Cabinet, responsible for handling
such appeals instead of the highest authority being at provincial
government and ministry levels.
</P>
<P>
But opponents said that they could see no reason to involve the
State Council in these matters because provincial and ministerial
organisations can be relied on to correct their own mistakes, if
any are found.
</P>
<P>
However, non-voting delegate Xu Bingzhong declared that there
was a need and quoted statistics to back up his claim.
</P>
<P>
"In the past seven years following the introduction of a set
of government regulation on administrative appeals, an annual
average of 1,500 complaints was brought to provincial-level
governments and ministries under the cabinet." he revealed.
</P>
<P>
"This is a considerably large number and it is inappropriate to
solely rely on those bodies to redress their own wrongdoings." he
added.
</P>
<P>
NPC Standing Committee vice-chairwoman Peng Peiyun said that
the State Council would be able to toughen up its own rules and
guidance on these issues of major significance if it is charged
with handling appeals against provincial governments and
ministries.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers commented that after previous discussions and
revisions, the draft law is now basically acceptable except that
further changes need to be made on the two issues mentioned above.
</P>
<P>
They advocated passing the law as soon as possible after such
changes had been made. 
</P>
</TEXT>
