<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai Branch of the
Bank of East Asia started its Renminbi-based business today,
thus becoming the tenth overseas bank in Shanghai doing the
yuan-based business.
</P>
<P>
According to provisional regulations on the yuan-based business
of overseas-funded financial institutions in the city's Pudong
Area, the bank is now allowed to do such businesses as deposits,
loans, accounts settlement, credit guarantees, national debt and
financial bonds investment and other RMB-related businesses.
</P>
<P>
The bank has already received applications for RMB loans from
both old customers in foreign currency business and some new
customers, said an official with the bank. He hoped that the
central bank would allow overseas-funded banks more lines of
financial business while strengthening an improved supervision and
management.
</P>
<P>
As the largest bank which is run by overseas Chinese in Hong
Kong, the Bank of East Asia opened a branch in Shanghai as early
as in 1920. The local branches of the bank in Shanghai and
Shenzhen have all gained permissions for RMB-based business.
</P>
