<HEADLINE> Khamenei Calls for Unity of Political Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Iranian supreme leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei on Friday urged rival political factions
in the country to set aside their disputes and get united.
</P>
<P>
A nation will suffer misery if the differences among its
people are aggravated, Khamenei addressed the Friday prayer
congregation on Tehran University campus.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was not referring to differences of taste or
policy, but political confrontation between rival factions "which
will cause tension," the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
"The hearts of the people will be broken to see there are
differences among high level officials," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also called on the press not to exaggerate the existing
differences, but to work to bring the political factions closer to
each other.
</P>
<P>
The moderates, headed by President Mohammad Khatami, and the
conservatives, who control most of the powers in the country,
engaged in a fierce power struggle this year due to sharp
differences over domestic and foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
Billing himself a strong advocate of freedom of expression,
Khamenei warned that some people are "taking advantage of this
freedom to create tension in society."
</P>
<P>
In October, Khamenei warned the press against overstepping the
freedom of expression. The warning was followed by a series of
crackdown on moderate and liberal publications by the
conservatives. 
</P>
