<HEADLINE> Toughest Year Ever For Chinese Red Cross </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) --Chinese Red Cross workers have
had the toughest year in their history as the country was hit by
natural disasters that affected at least 230 million people as
earthquakes, blizzards and floods raged.
</P>
<P>
However, despite the arduous relief work caused by successive
disasters the Red Cross Society of China (RCSC) says it managed to
cope with almost every eventuality.
</P>
<P>
It raised 770 million yuan (about 96 million U.S. dollars ) in
relief cash and materials and most of the donations reached the
disaster hit areas, according to RCSC spokesman Wu Qiusha.
</P>
<P>
Across China and throughout the year, more than 4,000 people
died during earthquakes, snow storms and floods, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
"The amount of manpower and material resources deployed for
disaster relief this year was the biggest in the 94-year history
of the RCSC," Wu Qiusha said.
</P>
<P>
The RCSC and its local branches raised about 90 million yuan,
10 million yuan and 670 million yuan respectively for quake-hit
Hebei Province, Tibet Autonomous Region and Qinghai Province
stricken by blizzards and for flooded areas along the Yangtze and
Nenjiang rivers.
</P>
<P>
Among the donations, more than 70 million yuan came from
foreign Red Cross and Red Crescent societies, as well as a number
of other international relief organizations.
</P>
<P>
The Red Cross societies in Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan also
provided 142.32 million yuan in relief funds, Wu added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
