<DOCNO> XIE19981225.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commentary:Who Are Japanese Courts Defending? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- A Tokyo high court's
rejection of World War II Japanese soldier Shiro Azuma's appeal
challenging a district court ruling on his personal diary is
politically motivated and the verdict will only further inflate
the arrogance of Japan's right-wingers.
</P>
<P>
The High Court of Tokyo ruled Tuesday that the Japanese
soldiers who were accused by Shiro Azuma in his war-time diary of
participating in the 1937 Nanking Massacre cannot be brought to
trial.
</P>
<P>
Shiro Azuma, 86, who took part in the attack on Nanjing
(formerly known as Nanking) in 1937, witnessed and kept a diary
on the hair-raising killings of Chinese servicemen and civilians.
The killings are known historically as the "Nanking Massacre."
</P>
<P>
Since the 1980s, a handful of Japanese right-wingers have
tried hard to whitewash Japan's history of aggression and flatly
denied the Nanking Massacre.
</P>
<P>
Shiro Azuma published the personal diary he kept during the
war in which he recorded the atrocities committed by the Japanese
soldiers and mentioned by name some of those who perpetrated the
bloody deeds.
</P>
<P>
In the spring of 1993, Koji Hashimoto, one of the soldiers
mentioned in the diary, sued Azuma for "damaging his reputation,"
with the intention of discrediting the Nanking Massacre.
</P>
<P>
On April 26, 1994, the Tokyo District Court ruled that the
Azuma diary "was judged as being unnatural by common sense" and
that Azuma pay the plaintiff 500,000 Japanese yen "in
compensation for damage to his reputation."
</P>
<P>
Azuma appealed to the High Court of Tokyo. However, his appeal
was rejected for the same reason on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
For years, right-wing political forces in Japan have been
trying to deny Japan's hostilities toward China. This denial of
the facts contained in the Azuma diary regarding the massacre
clearly demonstrates this tendency.
</P>
<P>
It is not merely a matter of how to interpret history
correctly, but also an issue of principle in Sino-Japanese
relations. If allowed to continue, such a tendency will seriously
weaken the political basis of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Nanking Massacre was far more cruel than Azuma
described in his diary. Nevertheless, the value of Azuma's diary
lies in its truthful presentation of the bloodshed and it serves
as a good textbook for more Japanese people to see a more
accurate picture of the Japanese war of aggression.
</P>
<P>
The rulings, which have always been favorable to the Japanese
right-wingers, are a distortion of history.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference, right-wingers led by Koji Hashimoto, o
penly displayed a streamer, which read, "We won in the hearings
on the fabricated Nanking Massacre!"
</P>
<P>
Although 50 years have passed since the war, some Japanese
still possess a biased view of history and many of them hold
posts in key offices in the government and other prestigious
organizations.
</P>
<P>
A recent example is that the granddaughter of Hideki Tojo, the
Number-One war criminal of World War II, has tried to reverse the
international verdict on her grandfather.
</P>
<P>
Only when Japan uses history as a mirror, rightly interprets
it and draws a correct lesson from it, can Japan stay on the
track of peaceful development. This is what Japan needs to think
about on the threshold of a new century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981225.0074 </DOCNO>
