<HEADLINE> Abubakar Named Man of Year 1998 by Time Magazine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar has been named among those who shaped the
year 1998 by the Time magazine in its current special edition.
</P>
<P>
In picking General Abubakar as one of the men of the year
1998, the magazine recalled the many years of suffering by the
Nigerians, corruption of unimaginable proportions, intimidation
and harassment of dissidents and ethnic rivalry among major
regions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ascension of Abubakar last June following the death of
former Head of State General Sani Abacha marked the beginning of
new lease of life for the Nigerians, the magazine stated.
</P>
<P>
Virtually unknown outside Nigeria, it noted, Abubakar has
surprised just about everyone by pledging one reform after
another and, more importantly, keeping his words since he took
office.
</P>
<P>
The magazine pointed out that the social and economic reforms
carried out by Abubakar within a short spell had endeared him to
the world and astonished his compatriots.
</P>
<P>
Unlike his predecessors, Abubakar stands out as a genuine
patriotic and honest leader, it said.
</P>
<P>
"By some accounts, Abacha and his family managed to salt away
several billions of Dollars in ill-gotten gains, largely from the
petroleum industry," said the magazine, adding that "yet Abubakar
has not made one false step."
</P>
<P>
He released political prisoners including 20 Ogonis whose
cases were widely seen as a test of sincerity, he has gone after
Abacha's assets, reclaiming some 750 million Dollars to date, he
promised best efforts to reconcile some 300 feuding ethnic groups
in the country, the magazine x-rayed the head of state.
</P>
<P>
"A land that had gained a reputation as the sick man of Africa
is finding cause for celebration at last," the American magazine
stressed. 
</P>
