<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Top Chinese Nuclear Physicist Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The body of Wang Ganchang, one
of China's most renowned nuclear physicists, was cremated today
at the Babaoshan revolutionary cemetery in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Wang, who died on December 10 at the age of 91, was one of
the pioneers and founders of China's experimental nuclear physics,
cosmic ray and particle physics.
</P>
<P>
A native of Changshu city in east China's Jiangsu Province,
Wang graduated from the Physics Department of Qinghua University
in 1929. He then studied in Germany and received a doctorate from
Berlin University in 1933. After returning to China in 1934, Wang
taught as a professor at Shandong and Zhejiang universities and
was one of the instigators of Chinese nuclear physics research.
</P>
<P>
Wang was among the top scientific experts who attained China's
breakthroughs in atomic bomb, hydrogen-bomb theory and nuclear
weapon research.
</P>
<P>
In an academic career spanning over 70 years, he trained three
generations of scientists, among them Nobel Prize winner Li
Zhengdao.
</P>
<P>
On his death, Chinese leaders including Jiang Zemin, Li Peng
and Zhu Rongji and distinguished scientists such as Li Zhengdao,
extended their condolences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
