<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Pollution in Dhaka Reaches High Level: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Air pollution in Dhaka, capital
of Bangladesh, has reached a very high level due to emission of
suspended particulate materials (SPM) by pollution vehicles at an
increasing rate.
</P>
<P>
The level of SPM has reached 2,600 micrograms per cubic meter,
The Bangladesh Observer daily newspaper Friday quoted a recent
survey conducted by the Department of Environment on the air
quality in the city as saying.
</P>
<P>
The present level of microgram in the air quality is much
higher than the acceptable level of 200 per cubic meter, the
survey noted.
</P>
<P>
Air pollutant materials are normally emitted from petrol,
diesel used in the vehicles as well as dust which create SPM
sulphur di-oxide and nitrogen di-oxide in the air.
</P>
<P>
The range of sulphur di-oxide in Dhaka city air is about 100
micrograms against the acceptable level of 80 microgram per cubic
meter, the survey shows.
</P>
<P>
The air pollution has been causing serious health hazards to
the dwellers in the city with a population of over nine million.
</P>
<P>
More and more pedestrians, especially on-duty-policemen put on
gauze marks for preventing themselves from inhaling hazardous air.
</P>
<P>
At present, about 160,000 motorized vehicles operate in Dhaka
metropolitan area, with about one-third of them having no fitness
certificates, and these vehicles are constantly emitting black
smoke and fumes polluting the air, according to Bangladesh Road
Transport Authority.  
</P>
</TEXT>
