<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Revenue Fall Calls for Action: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 25 (Xinhua) -- A "monumental" fall in Nigerian
government's revenue "calls for a very tough and drastic
decision," The Post Express Friday quoted a minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
Information and Culture Minister John Nwodo said Thursday in
Nigerian capital Abuja that the fall in oil price from 17 U.S.
Dollars per barrel to less than 10 Dollars at the international
market had caused a "monumental" fall in government's revenue.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Executive Council (FEC) met for two days this week
and approved a draft 1999 budget which was passed on to the joint
meeting of the Provisional Ruling Council and the National
Council of State which could not reach a decision on it after two
days of deliberations.
</P>
<P>
The difficulties of the nation's two highest ruling bodies at
putting a final seal on the budget were conveyed by the minister
after the joint meeting was adjourned till next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The minister noted that "we have a substantial and monumental
fall in revenue for factors totally outside the control of the
Federal Government of Nigeria."
</P>
<P>
"There is no way you can have a fall in revenue of 42 percent
without its effect being felt in the country," Nwodo said, adding
that Nigerians would appreciate the tough budgetary process.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the two bodies would conclude deliberations
on next year's budget next Tuesday, which would be announced in
the broadcast to the country by the head of state.
</P>
<P>
A reliable source said Thursday that the Nigerian government
may have canceled the controversial 5,200 Naira (about 60
Dollars) minimum wage decision which had caused unprecedented
protests throughout the country demanding its implementation of
300 percent wage increase.
</P>
<P>
A consensus reached at a meeting by government officials in
Abuja this week favored the scrapping of the package and
recommended that salaries of civil servants be doubled to meet
with the escalating cost of living.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the newly endorsed wage would reflect in
a statement which would be issued by the presidency soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
