<HEADLINE> Upper-Air Weather Forecast Stations Expected in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 25 (Xinhua) - The World Meteorological
Organization (WMO) aims to establish at least one functioning
upper-air weather station in each African country.
</P>
<P>
Director General of the Tanzania Directorate of Meteorology
Mohammed Mhita said that the office of the WMO Regional
Association for Africa (RAI) has planned to assist upgrading 21
upper-air weather stations in Africa to fully operational,
newspapers published here reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mhita, who was elected president of the RAI in its 12th
session held in Tanzanian northern town of Arusha in October,
said that the objective of the association is to mobilize
resources from donor countries to assist the upper-air stations
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The main obstacle facing the meteorology is communication
because it often becomes difficult to disseminate information of
adverse weather reports to remote areas in time to warn people of
pending natural disasters," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out the need for efficient workers in
departments of meteorology in the African continent.
</P>
<P>
Mhita said that at the Arusha session, which was attended by
41 African member states of RAI, various issues including the
floods caused by the El-Nino weather phenomenon in East Africa as
well as the drought experienced in the Southern Africa region
this year were discussed.
</P>
<P>
He said that Tanzania expects to construct an ultra-modern
upper-air station early next year in Dar es Salaam, where the RAI
office has been shifted to, but the running costs are as high as
100 U.S. Dollars a day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
