<HEADLINE> Khamenei Reiterates No Relations with U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Iran's paramount leader
Ayatollah Ali Khamenei said here Friday that Iran would not resume
relations with the U.S. if Washington has not changed its policies
towards Iran.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at Friday prayers at Tehran University, Khamenei said
that Iranians and the government would not reconcile with the
U.S. as long as it continues its "ill-intentions" against Iran.
</P>
<P>
"Our problem with the U.S. is not a resumption of relations,"
he said, "the U.S. wants to dictate its policies to other
governments, particularly the weak countries in the region, they
want to plunder rather than have an exchange (with Iran)."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that "the aim of the U.S. is hegemony, not
relations." "They want to again enjoy the political, economic and
security benefits they had for 30 years under the former regime,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The late shah's regime, which had had close ties with the U.S.,
collapsed in the Islamic revolution in 1979 that brought about the
rule of Islamic clerics.
</P>
<P>
The supreme leader is omnipotent in both domestic and foreign
affairs of Iran. Seen as leaning toward political conservatives,
Khamenei reportedly disliked reformist President Mohammad
Khatami's milder approach toward the U.S.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is wrongly assuming that the Iranian people have
turned their back to the Islamic revolution and their ideals,
Khamenei said. "Don't ever think that our nation will give in to
your pressure and bullying."
</P>
<P>
He told Washington: "As long as this nation stands by Islam,
they would not come to terms with you."
</P>
<P>
The two countries cut off diplomatic relations in 1980,
following the takeover of the U.S. embassy in Tehran by radical
students in the heyday of the Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
But Khamenei said Iran has no enmity toward the American
people, and it only does not trust the American government.
</P>
<P>
Iran is eager to have normal relations with the entire world
and is improving ties with Europe, Russia, Asia, Africa and all
other countries, he noted.
</P>
<P>
He also condemned the recent U.S.-British military strikes
against Iraq on "false excuses" and slammed the U.S. for its
interventions in all spots of crisis in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Whenever there is a problem in Afghanistan, the Persian Gulf,
the Middle East, Europe, etc. the U.S. interferes," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
