<HEADLINE> Tanzania Nets 15 Suspects on Cross-Border Car </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 25 (Xinhua) - Tanzanian police has
arrested 15 people suspected to be key members of a network of
international car robberies, media here reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
A senior police officer, quoted by the media, said Thursday
that the suspects are in connection with the theft of 165
vehicles from the southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
The Director of Criminal Investigation of the Home Affairs
Ministry, Adadi Rajabu, revealed that in a swoop in late August
which involved police detectives from all SADC member states, 89
vehicles were established to have been stolen in Tanzania while
76 were stolen from South Africa, Malawi and Swaziland.
</P>
<P>
He said that 50 vehicles have so far been released by the
police, but others have not been recovered since they do not meet
conditions for their clearance.
</P>
<P>
"We want the owners to come themselves personally to claim
their vehicles by producing original motor vehicle cards plus
ignition keys instead of sending insurance agents," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Rajabu said that the special operation, started in Malawi, has
also netted 27 guns and eight bullets in a bid to curb illegal
ownership of firearms as well as drug-related incidences. 
</P>
