<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guizhou Province Expects Growth Faster Than Nation's Average </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Guizhou
Province expects an annual GDP growth of 8.6 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Fangren, secretary of the provincial committee
of the Communist Party of China, this is the second consecutive
year that Guizhou has had an annual growth rate that is higher
than the nation's average.
</P>
<P>
Guizhou achieved a nine percent growth last year. Prior to
that, it had experienced tens years' economic development slower
than the nation's average.
</P>
<P>
Official projection expects the financial revenue of the
province to reach 11.7 billion yuan, a 9 percent increase over
last year, despite a 400- million-yuan revenue reduction in
tobacco.
</P>
<P>
Economists say China's sustainable growth needs a more balanced
picture, where the gap between the more developed coastal regions
and the less developed inland regions that cover the vast central
and western part come closer to each other, or at least the two
parts of the country grow at the same pace.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Economic and Trade Commission, China's
economic growth this year will be close to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
The fixed asset investments of Guizhou are expected to be 31.5
billion yuan, or 22.6 percent more than last year. A number of
infrastructure projects were started early this year, with the
focus on transportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
