<DOCNO> XIE19981225.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Steps Up Expansion of Inland River Shipping Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai will appropriate a
total of 1.6 billion yuan for expanding its existing inland river
shipping network in the next couple of years.
</P>
<P>
The project will require construction of major shipping routes
to the neighboring Jiangsu and Zhejiang provinces by expanding and
dredging the river courses, including routes for container ships,
and will be finished by the year 2005.
</P>
<P>
By then, Shanghai will have 500 km of shipping routes to
accommodate 300-dwt (dead weight tonnages) ships and boats, and
another 1,100 km to accommodate 100-dwt ships, and will be
connected to other areas south of the Yangtze River through its
expanded inland river shipping network, whereby 150 million tons
of cargo will be shipped annually, said local sources.
</P>
<P>
In 2010, 1.2 million TEUs of containers will be transported by
the city's inland river shipping network.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the city has 44 inland river ports and 3,000 berths,
and has 2,100 km of inland river shipping routes, of which, only
451 km are capable of accommodating 100-dwt ships and boats and
another 40 km capable of accommodating 500-dwt ships and boats.
</P>
<P>
Last year, 129 million tons of cargo were shipped through
inland river shipping services of Shanghai, accounting for one
quarter of the city's total cargo transportation volume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
