<HEADLINE> PAL Talks With Cathay, Northwest Still on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Hongkong-based Cathay
Pacific Airways and the U.S.-based Northwest Airlines are still
holding separate talks with the Philippine Airlines (PAL) on a
possible major stake in the ailing national carrier, a senior
official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a Radio interview Friday morning, Executive Secretary
Ronaldo Zamora said that aside from Cathay and Northwest, a number
of prospective investors have also expressed interest in a
possible buy-in deal that would keep the debt-saddled PAL on air.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, these separate talks are being held in
private to avoid hitches.
</P>
<P>
"The discussions are still going on, but these are not being
made public for the moment to avoid snags. They're talking in
private," Zamora said.
</P>
<P>
That is why PAL is still hopeful that its talks with either
Cathay Pacific or Northwest would produce positive results, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Zamora also reiterated the position of President Joseph Estrada
that the government will always be prepared to help out but not to
take over PAL.
</P>
<P>
Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu warned Thursday that PAL
would be closed again if it fails to find new investors.
</P>
<P>
The financially-troubled airline was closed in September but
resumed operation in October after the government helped in
resolving a labor dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
