<HEADLINE> Fake Seeds Hurt Zambian Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's seed industry has
described this year's planting season as the worst in the history
of agricultural production of the country because of the rampant
fake seeds dealing.
</P>
<P>
Anne Chipill, chief agricultural officer of the Seed Control
and Certification Institute (SCCI), said that the illegal seeds
sold to the farmers may affect this season's harvest, Zambia
Daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
She was quoted as telling a monthly Agricultural Science
Association of Zambia fora held here that investigations and
inspections carried out by SCCI have shown that almost every
district in the country have been affected.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Zambia Seed Company managing director Winter
Chibasa has called for concerted efforts from stakeholders in the
industry to solve the problem of vending seeds.
</P>
<P>
He said seed is a delicate commodity which could not be sold
on the streets.
</P>
<P>
Chibasa said that many farmers have been cheated and swindled
by vendors who are selling fake seeds. 
