<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Gorges Dam Water to Be Cleaned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing, China's youngest
municipality in the southwest, will launch an ambitious
cross-century environmental program to substantially improve the
quality of the much-polluted Yangtze River water at the Three
Gorges Dam area.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that more than 100 million tons of industrial
and residential sewage is being discharged into the Three Gorges
Dam area, half of which falls far below the national sewage
discharge standards.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges dam is the world's largest hydropower
facility under construction.
</P>
<P>
At the first stage of the environmental protection program,
Chongqing will clean up garbage piled on river banks and floating
in the water as well as other pollutants in about one year.
</P>
<P>
The second stage project, hopefully starting the end of 1999,
will be focused on the disposal of residential wastes and
protection of drinking water sources at a cost of more than four
billion yuan, including loans from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
At the final stage, 12 billion yuan is expected to be
channeled to build 35 sewage disposal plants with a combined
daily handling capacity of 2.87 million tons and 34 garbage disp
osal plants with a total daily capacity of 8,900 tons. These
projects are expected to be completed around the year 2010.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
