<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Funds Play Important Role in Chinese Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Overseas-funded enterprises,
an alien entities only 20 years ago, currently employs 17.5
million Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics released by the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) show that the 304,800
overseas-funded enterprises China approved by the end of 1997
involved a total contracted volume of 521.16 billion U.S.
dollars. The 145,000 enterprises are now in operation.
</P>
<P>
A recent article by MOFTEC Minister Shi Guangsheng
pointed out that foreign-funded ventures have played an important
role in boosting China's comprehensive national strength.
</P>
<P>
China has absorbed a total of 221.87 billion dollars in foreign
direct investment (FDI) over the past 20 years and ranked as the
world's second largest recipient of FDI for five successive years
from 1993 to 1997, following the United States.
</P>
<P>
In addition, over 140 billion US dollars in loans from foreign
governments and international financial institutions have poured
into China.
</P>
<P>
China's use of foreign funds has surged since 1992. The
nation has improved its investment environment and formulated
a series of policies to encourage foreign investment in central
and western areas, as well as capital- and technology-intensive
industries, according to Shi.
</P>
<P>
More transnational enterprises have invested in China,
and the number of projects involving large funding continues to
increase.
</P>
<P>
Shi said China will open its service trade to foreign investors
step by step. 
</P>
</TEXT>
