<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU December 25 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong
province plans to spend 30 million yuan (3.6 million U.S. dollars)
over the next three years to fight a disastrous blight that is
killing pine trees.
</P>
<P>
The blight, which appeared in Guangdong nine years ago, is
caused by a worm that burrows into the pines and can kill them in
a short period of time. It is reported to be spreading fast.
</P>
<P>
The provincial forestry department has committed itself to the
pest control work, but the disease is still there. So, the
Ministries of Forestry and Finance are now paying close attention,
and the pine disease control has been listed among state-level
forest programs this year.
</P>
<P>
A special fund of 10 million yuan will also be allocated
annually by the central and provincial governments to pay for the
project for the next three years, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government will have a number of measures to
block off diseased areas, cut down infected trees, and sterilize
diseased forests, local officials say.  
</P>
