<HEADLINE> Gauze Masks Help People Of Lanzhou Deal With Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 25 (Xinhua) -- It's not uncommon this winter
to see the people of Lanzhou, the capital of Gansu Province in
northwestern China, walking around wearing a sort of gauze mask
over their nose and mouth.
</P>
<P>
This is how they try to stop the assault of dust in the air and
the worsening pollution in this industrial center, where breathing
fresh and clean air, even in the early morning, is a luxury.
</P>
<P>
Liu Lan, a worker who recently was laid-off by her textile
factory, now peddles gauze masks in the downtown area, and says
she can sell more than 50 of them every morning. She complains
that it has not rained since September, and the air is unbearably
dirty.
</P>
<P>
The city is flanked by mountains to the north and south, so it
has poor ventilation. And, fast economic growth and the use of
large amounts of coal for heating in the winter have caused the
further deterioration of air quality.
</P>
<P>
When seen from above, the city is shrouded in a thick dark
cloud. In fact, the city's air quality has been at level 5 since
late September, the worst level in air quality. The main
pollutants are dust and sluphur dioxide.
</P>
<P>
For years, the city government has tried to curb pollution by
planting trees, improving boilers, and closing down polluting
factories, but doesn't seem to have got very far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
