<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Chinese Firms Vie for Import, Export Authority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- China's new policy to grant
import and export authority to some private manufacturers have
been well received as the policy will take effect within a week.
</P>
<P>
A dozen firms including China's largest animal feed producer,
the Xiwang (Hope) Group in southwest China's Sichuan Province,
have applied for the authority with the Ministry of Foreign Trade
and Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC), an official with the Foreign
Trade Policy and Development Department of MOFTEC said.
</P>
<P>
Most applicants come from Sichuan, south China's Guangdong
Province, east China's Jiangxi Province and Tianjin Municipality
in northern China. Many other private enterprises have called the
MOFTEC for detailed information.
</P>
<P>
The applicants are engaged in such industries as animal feed,
wood and mineral processing, foodstuffs, chemicals, agricultural
development, construction materials, textiles, electronics and
machinery, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
He said that those who have passed qualification examinations
will begin to receive permits as of January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Applicants must have a registered capital of at least 8.50
million yuan (about 1.03 million US dollars), and an annual
turnover of 50 million yuan (about 6.04 million US dollars). The
annual turnover of electronic companies must reach 30 million yuan
and that of machinery companies, 10 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade business was monopolized by state-owned
trade companies for a long time. State-owned large and
medium-sized companies were granted the authority in the
1980s. Private companies had to rely on trade companies for their
import and export business.
</P>
<P>
The new move to grant import and export authority to private
manufacturers is part of MOFTEC efforts to boost China's foreign
trade next year, experts said, citing China's declining exports
this year as a consequence of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"In so doing, we encourage the efficient companies to break
into the international market and set a good image for the
international community," Sun Zhenyu, MOFTEC vice-minister, said
in a meeting earlier this week. "They have great potential in the
international market from a long-term perspective."
</P>
<P>
The vice-minister said that there will be no ceiling to the
number of private manufacturing companies permitted to handle
imports and exports.
</P>
<P>
Private enterprises have been becoming an increasingly
important force in China's economic growth. By the end of June of
1998, more than 1.04 million private firms, with a total
registered capital of 65.5 million US dollars, had been set up in
China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981225.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Foreign Trade Grows Rapidly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Twenty years ago, China's
foreign trade volume only accounted for 8.8 percent of the
country's gross national product (GNP), but now it made up
more than one third of China's GNP.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show China's foreign trade amounted to 325.06
billion US dollars last year, pushing China into the top 10
largest traders in the world. However, China only ranked 32nd
with a total trade volume of 20.6 billion US dollars in 1978.
</P>
<P>
China has witnessed rapid development of foreign trade over the
past two decades, Chinese Trade Minister Shi Guangsheng commented
in a recent signed article.
</P>
<P>
After China adopted the policy of reform and opening-up in
1978, foreign trade has been expanded, and become a crucial part
in the growth of national economy and social development, he said.
</P>
<P>
From 1978 to 1997, China's foreign trade increased at an
average annual rate of 15.6 percent, eight percent higher than the
world's average.
</P>
<P>
China now has 227 trade partners all over the world, while in
1978 it traded with only dozens of countries and regions.
</P>
<P>
Shi contributed the achievements to sustained development of
the national economy, a socialist market economy and the rise in
China's international status.
</P>
<P>
The Ninth Five-Year Plan (1996-2000) and the Long-Range
Objective through the Year 2010 have set the target of China's
foreign trade at 400 billion US dollars in 2000, and at 800
billion in 2010.
</P>
<P>
In his article, Shi vows to expand the scale of foreign trade
to gain more economic returns to meet the above goals. He said
China will continue the structural reform of its foreign trade
sector, explore new international markets, and forge bilateral and
multilateral trade ties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981225.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Credits to Push Forward Chinese Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Consumer credits are expected
to play a significant role in expanding China's domestic demand,
which has been listed by the Chinese government as a key task for
next year's economic work.
</P>
<P>
China's state-owned commercial banks have recently opened
automobile consumption credit business with approval of the
People's Bank of China, indicating that the Chinese government has
begun to tap the potential of consumer credits to further push
forward the country's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Consumer credit refers to loans extended by commercial banks to
consumers for buying durable goods. In many countries consumer
credit constitutes a considerable ratio of bank loans, while
in China it is still at a fairly low level.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy has been picking up over the past months,
largely due to increased government spending. Experts agreed that
a sustained and healthy national economic development can not rely
solely on investment. Instead it needs to stimulate residents'
consumption demand to ensure a coordinated growth of both
consumption and investment.
</P>
<P>
They noted that the expansion of consumer credits can help
change consumers' traditional consumption concept and make it
possible to tap consumption potential, so as to effectively
propel economic growth.
</P>
<P>
In contrast to investment and export, consumption demand has
been playing an increasingly significant role in stimulating
China's economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that consumption contributed 55 percent to
China's economic growth in 1997, while up to 80 percent of the
total consumption came from consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
By the end of November, the outstanding amount of China's
residents' savings deposits in financial institutions reached 5.29
trillion yuan, up 18 percent from the same period last year, which
laid a solid foundation for the development of consumer credits.
</P>
<P>
As an emerging banking business, consumer credits are currently
available mainly in automobile and housing consumption. With the
deepening of the housing reform and an increasing number
of private cars, consumer credits are expected to have vigorous
development in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
Financial experts said that the government should provide more
policy support for the development of consumer credits, and that
commercial banks should also offer more banking services to
individuals.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981225.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
