<HEADLINE> Croatian Border with Southern Yugoslavia Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Croatia's border with southern
Yugoslavia in the Prevalka area has been opened after having been
closed for seven years, the Croatian News Agency said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Under a bilateral agreement, the common border between Croatia
and the Montenegro Republic of Yugoslavia in this disputed area
will stay open until January 15,1999 for people there to visit
each other in New Year holidays.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time the two countries opened this section
of border since the disintegration of the former Yugoslavia in
1991, after months of negotiations.
</P>
<P>
In the former Yugoslavia, the Prevalka peninsula belonged to
Croatia, but Belgrade now claims sovereignty over it, saying that
it is a vital access to sea for Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
A U.N. Security Council resolution placed the region under the
control of U.N. observers to prevent possible border conflicts
and led to the closure of the border.
</P>
<P>
Because of the border closure, the two countries incurred
enormous economic losses so they now wish to settle the dispute
through negotiation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
