<HEADLINE> Large Petro-Chem Venture Suggests Early Investment in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, December 25 (Xinhua) -- "You can't be too picky about a
place like Ningbo. It's best you make your investment here now
instead of waiting too long," said Raymond Wang, a general manager
of the local subsidiary of a large international petro-chemical
company, in a recent interview here.
</P>
<P>
Ningbo is a coastal city in east China's Zhejiang Province. Its
Beilun port is China's largest deep-water international port.
</P>
<P>
Wang's company, Esso SinoChem (Ningbo) Petroleum and
Petrochemicals Supply Co., Ltd. is the first investment in
Zhejiang by Exxon, the largest petroleum company of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
Infrastructure construction is in full swing in China, which is
a great business opportunity for international companies, Wang
said. And overseas investors should have a keener business sense,
and work out a long-term plan for the China business.
</P>
<P>
He agreed that the investment environment in Ningbo and in
China as a whole is not perfect right now, but pointed out that
"when everything is perfect, business will be more costly and the
opportunity left for you will be smaller."
</P>
<P>
Esso SinoChem is building a 50,000-ton dock at Beilun, and runs
a lubricant manufacturer with a production capacity of 35,000
tons. In addition to Esso SinoChem, Exxon has set up three other
subsidiaries in Ningbo. The total investments stand at 85 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Exxon does not expect short-term return from its facilities in
Ningbo, according to Wang. "It won't be easy to make money out of
the 50,000-ton dock in a decade, but you have to count on the
future, because Ningbo is getting better day by day."
</P>
<P>
The Ningbo government has implemented a set of rules to
encourage overseas investment to involve in high technology, and
airport, port, highway, power, energy, water conservancy and
environmental protection projects.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors in the above-mentioned areas are exempt from
corporate income tax for different periods of time and will get
partial or full tax refunds after the exemption periods are over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
