<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Residents Turn to Long-Term Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 25 (Xinhua) -- A new trend is emerging in
south China's economic center of Guangzhou where an increasing
number of local residents regard investment for the future as
more important than consumption for the present.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey of 10,000 households conducted by the city
government shows that Guangzhou residents are now more
investment-conscious.
</P>
<P>
Investment modes such as bank deposits, education, insurance,
real estate, and stocks and bonds now account for the majority of
surplus household income, with home redecorating, interior
remodeling, travel, electrical appliances and cars a close second.
</P>
<P>
Experts say this is a result of the steady increase in income
for the people of Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
About 94.9 percent of those surveyed choose to save some
surplus income in the bank, with 70 percent of them saying this
is their first choice.
</P>
<P>
Despite reduced interest rates for savings accounts in recent
years, the bank is still attractive because of the continuing
slow rate of inflation.
</P>
<P>
However, experts predict that individual investments will
become more diversified as insurance and real estate purchases
become more attractive.
</P>
<P>
The survey shows that different income levels lead to
divergent spending and saving habits. Households with higher
incomes tend to invest more in securities, and spend more on
travel.
</P>
<P>
Families with lower incomes put their money first in
insurance, education and household furnishings.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981225.0147 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Considers Incentives for Garment Back-Linkage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government is
considering some incentives for the back-linkage industries of
garment sector which faces the problem for changes in the GSP
(generalized system of preference) rule for apparel export to
European countries, according to Commerce and Industries Minister
Tofael Ahmed.
</P>
<P>
Although the new GSP facility based on two-stage derogation
would help garment export grow substantially, the back-linkage
industries of the sector would be in serious problem, the minister
was quoted Friday by The New Nation newspaper as saying Thursday
after the 5th meeting of the National Committee on Export.
</P>
<P>
"The back-linkage industries will face problem due to the new
GSP facility and we will have to find ways to minimize the
problems," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Under a unilateral decision, the European Union (EU) will
concede two-stage derogation to knitwear and one-stage to woven
garments from January 1, 1999 for the least developed countries,
instead of previous provision for three and two stages, according
to the changed GSP rules.
</P>
<P>
He and the finance minister would meet with the industrial
owners who would be harmed by the new rules and assess the extent
of probable damages, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government would surely extend some sort of incentives to
them, but the modes of incentive are yet to be decided, he added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Bangladeshi Commerce Ministry had requested the EU
to continue the previous GSP along with the derogation facilities
until necessary back-linkage industries were set up in the country
to feed the apparel industry.
</P>
<P>
The EU rejected Bangladesh's appeal for continuing previous GSP
for the country, and the re-defined GSP comes into effect in next
January.
</P>
<P>
The garment sector, which has over 2,700 registered apparel
manufacturers and exporters employing some 1.5 million workers, is
the country's biggest foreign exchange earner.
</P>
<P>
It earned about 3.8 billion U.S. dollars in the 1997-98 fiscal
year ending on June 30, 1998, contributing about 70 percent to the
country's foreign currency earnings. Its export target this year
is about 4.5 billion dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
