<HEADLINE> Housing Reform Progress In Southern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 25 (Xinhua) -- China's Guangdong Province
has sold about 80 percent of its publicly-owned residential
buildings to tenants as the country's housing reforms move ahead.
</P>
<P>
The province's banks have already issued mortgages worth about
two billion yuan (240.96 million U.S. dollars) to some 30,000
individual home buyers, accounting for about 80 percent of the
housing deals here.
</P>
<P>
Another part of the reform is an increase in housing rents for
those still living in public housing. In Guangzhou, the rents are
now 2.3 yuan per square meter.
</P>
<P>
The province has sold 1.14 million flats covering 83.69 million
square meters of floor space and has taken in 15.55 billion yuan in
the process.
</P>
<P>
As more people prepare to buy their own homes, the province has
spent more than 50 billion yuan on housing construction each year
in recent years. 
</P>
