<HEADLINE> Leading Producers in China to Stabilize Sugar Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- China's three major sugar
producers have decided to apply regulated sugar prices suggested
by the State Development Planning Commission to avoid price war.
</P>
<P>
Sugar producing Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region and Guangdong
and Yunnan provinces in southern China have reached consensus on
the new prices with a view to stabilizing the market, according
to industry sources.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi, Guangdong and Yunnan produce six million tons of
sugar a year, accounting for 90 percent of China's total, with
five million tons sold to other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
The price of sugar has been declining in China for years
mainly due to the cut-throat price war.
</P>
<P>
To strengthen its regulation of the sugar market, China will
also continue to crack down hard on sugar smuggling and exert
control over the production and sales of saccharin, according to
official sources.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, a Guangxi regional government
official said that the purchasing price of sugar cane in the
region has been set at 180 yuan per ton for the new sugar
pressing season, but a margin of 10 percent is allowed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
