<HEADLINE> Mexico Takes Measures to Protect Rare Turtle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Mexico has taken various
measures to protect rare sea turtles, on both national and local
levels, authorities said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Fishing Research Center of Tamaulipas state, bordering
with the United States on the Gulf of Mexico, said 3,658 parrot
turtle nests have been kept under vigilance this year to
safeguard them from poachers.
</P>
<P>
A total of 181,764 turtles have been released into the
wildness to rescue the species from the brink of extinction.
</P>
<P>
In April every year, the turtles start to arrive at the
Tamaulipas beaches, where they stay to hatch eggs from the end of
October to the first days of November.
</P>
<P>
The turtle protection programs, being extended to all the
beaches where the species goes to lay eggs, are under the
administration of Mexico's Navy Ministry and the Environment,
Natural Resources and Fishing Ministry, the center said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
