<HEADLINE> Thai Health Officials Dislike Giving Gifts to Seniors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Christmas is the time for
gift-giving, but officials from the Public Health Ministry of
Thailand dislike the practice.
</P>
<P>
According to the result of an opinion poll available Friday,
most health officials disagree with the norm of providing
expensive gifts to their administrators during the new year, which
has become a traditional practice among health officials in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
The poll was conducted by a doctor and his team of doctors, who
are vocal about the health ministry's corruption.
</P>
<P>
The poll showed that 65 percent of the health officials felt
that this practice had a 60-100 percent chance of benefiting the
person's working status. Out of the 4,041 questionnaires
distributed to health officials in eight provinces and Bangkok,
2,536, or 62 percent, were returned to the Public Health
Conservation and Protection Network.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-five percent of the officials disagreed with purchasing
expensive gifts for their bosses and 79 percent felt that state
officials should not receive sponsorship from private companies.
</P>
</TEXT>
