<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Bosnian Serb parliament
Thursday voted to reject a prime minister nominee forwarded by
President Nikola Poplasen, Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
A resolution endorsed at the parliamentary session said that
the parliament decided to nominate incumbent Prime Minister
Milorad Dodik for another term since Poplasen's nominee Dragan
Kolinic has failed to win a majority of votes in
parliament.
</P>
<P>
Deputies from the Serbian Radical Party and Serbian Democratic
Party withdrew in protest in the middle of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Poplasen, leader of the Serbian Radical Party, replaced
Biljana Plavsic, a moderate backed by U.S.-led western countries,
to become president of the Serbs' Republic of Bosnia in September.
</P>
<P>
In mid-November, Poplasen nominated Kolinic, leader of the
hard-line Serbian Democratic party, as prime minister, which
added to displeasure of the West.
</P>
<P>
Carlos Westerndorp, High Representative of Peace
Implementation Council of Bosnia, repeatedly claimed that Dodik
was the ideal candidate for premiership.
</P>
<P>
He even threatened that the international community would
suspend all aids to the Republic unless Dodik continues to be
prime minister. 
</P>
