<HEADLINE> Myanmar Industrial Zone to Add Golf Course </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 25 (Xinhua) -- A world-class golf course and
golf club and an advanced housing estate will be set up in
Myanmar's developing Hlaingtharya Industrial Zone in the northwest
of Yangon.
</P>
<P>
The Hlaingtharya zone is one of the five of its kind being
established in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract signed here Thursday between the Human
Settlement and Housing Development Department of the Myanmar
Ministry of Construction and the Yangon Nominees Co. Ltd., a
subsidiary of the FMI Group of local companies, the entire project
will be implemented on a 264-hectare plot at a cost of over 23
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 453-hectare Hlaingtharya Industrial Zone was initially
developed by local entrepreneurs who set up such industries as
food processing, textile, engineering, electrical goods,
chemicals, forest products and animal feed.
</P>
<P>
The development of the zone was later joined by multi-national
foreign firms including those from Britain, France, Japan,
Singapore and Thailand, as well as Myanmar-foreign joint ventures,
by leasing land and running dairy products, galvanized iron sheet,
and sanitary and garment factories.
</P>
<P>
After Thailand's Rojana Industrial Park Co. Ltd. joined the
infrastructure development of the zone in April 1997 with an
investment of 14 million dollars, the zone became the third
foreign-invested one after the Mingaladon developed by Japan's
Mitsui and the Thanlyin-Kyauktan established by Singapore's
Sinmardev and Malaysia's Genting Sayen Berhad. The remaining two
are entirely locally-invested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
