<HEADLINE> Thailand to Seek More Loans for School Dropouts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The Education Ministry of
Thailand is to seek an additional 500 million baht (13.9 million
U.S. dollars) from state coffers to bring the dropouts back to
school, the Bangkok Post newspaper reported here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will also provide loans to needy students, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Sa-ngob Laksana, deputy permanent secretary for education, said
a 1,000-million baht (27.8 million dollar) loan was insufficient
to meet the rising number of loan seekers.
</P>
<P>
The loan, granted by the Asian Development Bank, is aimed at
helping 215,722 dropouts and poor students from primary and
secondary schools nationwide.
</P>
<P>
So far, a total of 313,211 students and dropouts have applied
for the loans, according to Sa-ngob, who is the deputy chairman of
the ministry's loan scheme.
</P>
<P>
The ministry has asked schools in all provinces to submit lists
of dropouts and needy students by March 31 next year.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that the number of loan seekers will rise to
120,000. 
</P>
