<HEADLINE> Mexican Government Hopes to Resume Talks With Rebels in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 24 (Xinhua) -- The Mexican government
will step up efforts in the coming year to resume peace talks
with the country's armed rebels, chief government negotiator
Emilio Rabasa said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The leftist Zapatist Army of National Liberation (EZLN) took
up arms in southeastern Chiapas state on the New Year's Day in
1994, demanding greater democracy and rights for impoverished
Indian communities.
</P>
<P>
Scores of people were killed in the conflicts before the
Zapatistas retreated into jungles to become a guerrilla force.
</P>
<P>
Dialogue between the government and the EZLN has been on and
off in the past four years, with the last round of peace talks
suspended in September 1996 due to disagreement over indigenous
legislation.
</P>
<P>
Rabasa said in a communique that the government is open for
discussion of any plan to remove obstacles in the talks,
including even the establishment of a mediation group, which, he
said, should be "national and professional."
</P>
<P>
He ruled out the possibility of an international mediation to
solve the problem, saying "it is not necessary, not justified,
and the matter does not merit it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
