<HEADLINE> Panama to Resume Tuna Fishing, Marketing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, December 24 (Xinhua) -- Panama would restart tuna
fishing in the Pacific Ocean next February following the United
States' lift of its embargo on tuna fishing and marketing, an
official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The move, said Marine Resources Administration director
Arnulfo Franco, would help Panama recover losses amounting to 150
billion U.S. dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. tuna embargo was initially applied to Mexico in 1991
and later extended to Southern Pacific nations in response to
environmentalists' allegation that tuna capture kills dolphins as
the imperiled species often get snared in tuna nets.
</P>
<P>
Now a limited tuna capture is allowed, Franco said. Panama,
Mexico, Ecuador and Venezuela have jointly ratified the Panama
Declaration to protect the dolphin.
</P>
<P>
The lift of embargo would ensure a resumption of tuna fishing
and marketing activities as well as promote the development of
Vacamonte Port on the Pacific coasts, where there are 322 tuna
ships and 56 cargo ships, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Two Panamanian firms have installed tuna processing facilities
in Puerto Vacamonte, creating new job opportunities for the
country, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
