<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Reform Its Cotton Circulation System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The State Council of China has
decided to reform the country's cotton circulation system in 1999
to make the sector fully market-oriented.
</P>
<P>
The reform includes cancellation of traditional government-set
cotton purchase prices and allowing textile companies and other
related economies to buy cotton directly from farmers, rather
than the monopoly held by the All-China Federation of Supply and
Marketing Co-operatives.
</P>
<P>
The government will only issue the reference price before the
purchasing season, which is estimated to be around 500 yuan (60.3)
per 50 kilograms, or 10 yuan a kilogram, in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The current cotton purchasing price was set at the
government-fixed rate of 700 yuan per kilogram, a radical
difference.
</P>
<P>
It's estimated that nearly 2 million tons of cotton have been
stockpiled across the country. In order to balance the stockpile
of domestic cotton, the government for the first time introduced
market mechanisms to this long-protected sector in April by
allowing the purchase price to float between five percent on a
basis of 650 yuan per 50 kg.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that the exemption of cotton price control is also
part of government measures to save costs for textile companies,
most of which are running at loss.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Agriculture predicted that the
purchasing price will see a big plunge next year while the
cotton-planting areas will also be reduced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
