<HEADLINE> China's First Joint-Stock Offshore Oil Company Established </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 25 (Xinhua) -- China Offshore Oil Co., Ltd.,
the first joint-stock offshore oil producer in the country, was
inaugurated Thursday in the northern port city of Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
The new company is jointly financed by China Offshore Oil
Corporation, Bohai Oil Company, Western Oil Company and Eastern
Oil Company of South China Sea Oil Company, and East China Sea Oil
Company, at a cost of 1.319 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China Offshore Oil Corporation uses oil drilling platforms at
three zones of the Suizhong 36-1 oil field and part of the fixed
assets, auxiliary equipment, property and working capital as its
capital share in the new company, while the other partners inject
cash, according to Wei Liucheng, general manager of China Offshore
Oil Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The new company will soon apply for issuing shares to raise
estimated two billion yuan in fund. All the money raised will be
used to finance the second phase project of the oil field.
</P>
<P>
Suizhong 36-1 oil field, with 300 million tons of proven oil
reserves, is currently the largest oil field on the sea. It has a
designed production capacity of more than five million tons a
year, and is expected to pump 1.7 million tons of oil this year.
</P>
<P>
The heavy oil from its wells is fine raw materials for
producing high-quality asphalt recommended by the Chinese Ministry
of Communications.
</P>
<P>
China Offshore Oil Corporation has 30,000 employees, and
produces 16 million tons of crude and over four billion cubic
meters of natural gas annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
