<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese People Spend More on Posts and Telecommunications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 25 (Xinhua) -- The rapid development of posts
and telecommunications services has meant more convenient methods
for Chinese people to communicate with each other, and raised
their expenditure in this sector as a result.
</P>
<P>
Per capita expenditures in the sector have amounted to 96 yuan
monthly in 1998 compared to 1.72 yuan in 1980, according to a
survey carried out in 12 Chinese cities by the State Statistics
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
The survey also shows that the number of people writing letters
has dropped from 87 percent in 1980 to 15 percent in 1998; the
number of telegrams has fallen to 3 percent from 12 percent; and
that telephone users have increased by some 90 percent from the
former 8 percent eighteen years ago.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are more than 50 telephones for every 100
persons in most Chinese cities, and there are 60 to 90 phones per
100 citizens in the major cities of Beijing, Shanghai, Hangzhou,
Guangzhou, Shenzhen and Xiamen.
</P>
<P>
And the numbers of electronic beeper users and Internet
browsers have also increased markedly. There were only an
estimated four beepers per thousand people in 1980, while in 1998
the figure stands at 26 percent per hundred. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981225.0204 </DOCNO>
