<HEADLINE> Estrada Calls on Filipinos to Meet New Millennium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada has called for unity, hard work and perseverance to enable
Filipinos to meet the challenges of the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
In his Christmas message published here Friday, Estrada urged
Filipinos to "seize the moment and shun negative traits that have
hampered our progress as a nation."
</P>
<P>
He said that in spite of the extreme economic crisis that has
gripped Asia since last year, the country was able to escape a
recession and will be able to register a slight positive growth
next year, unlike other countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, in the course of his recent official visit to
other Southeast Asian countries, he had noticed that the
Philippines appears to be lagging behind its neighbors, despite
its "almost boundless capacity in natural and manpower resources."
</P>
<P>
"Now, the time has come for us to stand up and make things
happen. I know that we, as a people, have the inner strength and
resiliency, as proven by our ability to rise from one grave
challenge after another, in the course of our proud and glorious
history," he added.
</P>
<P>
"We have passed the darkest hour and weathered the eye of the
storm. Let us seize the moment -- to move forward, never looking
back, over our divisiveness, over our negative attitudes, so that
we can concretize our centerpiece programs geared to achieve
economic and social equality for the poor, peace and order, and
food security for all," President Estrada said.
</P>
<P>
He said unity among Filipinos should be the bedrock of their
progress and their capital to face the challenge and opportunities
of globalization in the next millennium. 
</P>
