Marcus Camby and Toronto Raptors forward Reggie Slater asked for
a court hearing seeking an injunction in the suit directed
against USA Basketball - the bridge between the NBA and FIBA,
basketball's interantioanl governing body.
</P>
<P>
The hearing is set for Deceber 30. European rosters are set
for the playoffs by January 1.
</P>
<P>
"Our position is there is no basketball season, no salary
being paid and no prospect for talks," attorney James Bryant
said. "Based on that, we believe this year's contract is moot."
</P>
<P>
A favorable ruling would not only fee the players to play in
the Euroeap but possibly make them free agents, which could have
repercussions for all locked-out NBA players under contract. All
three are in the final year of their contracts.
</P>
<P>
"All three want to be with their NBA teams, " Bryant said.
"But they need a job."
</P>
<P>
Russ Granik, USA Basketball President and also deputy
commissioner of the NBA, said: "We don't understand what USA
Basektball has to do with this. We don't pass judgment on the
validity of NBA contracts. In terms of eligibility with NBA
players, that's between the NBA and FIBA."
</P>
<P>
FIBA requires that players get unconditional release from
their NBA contracts before signing with European teams. Once a
player is released, USA Basketball processes the clearance with
FIBA.
</P>
<P>
NBA commissioner David Stern has said NBA players are free to
play for FIBA teams, but those under contract must return to the
league if the lockout ends. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
